description:
What if the price of every laugh was your own happiness? Jimmy Fallon reveals the shocking toll of his comedy empire. 

Jimmy Fallon is host of ‘The Tonight Show’, Emmy-winning comedian and television personality, and former host of ‘Saturday Night Live’ (SNL). He is also the author of children’s and comedy books such as, 'Papa Doesn't Do Anything!’ and is set to launch a new innovative marketing show called ‘On Brand with Jimmy Fallon’ this Fall. 

Jimmy discusses:
◽️ How he didn’t expect the entertainment industry to be so brutal.
◽️ Why his sense of humour became his secret weapon.
◽️ How he navigated receiving hate after achieving massive success in comedy.
◽️ How his strict Catholic upbringing shaped his relentless need to please others.
◽️ How his mother’s support gave him the confidence to chase his dreams.

Instead, he is here at a time when studios are pushing political agendas and forcing the shows to implement them. Fallon held out the longest but in the end still had to compromise to keep his job and so The Tonight Show just blends in with the others, looking and acting the same. It used to be that the late shows were all vastly different from each other and today they all come off as mouth pieces and that is a damn shame because Fallon's first 8 years as a host (late night with Fallon from 2009 and first 3 years with Tonight Show) were unique and fantastic...then the studios pushed TDS for ratings and the show lost its charm and became just like the others.

comments.text: @shaynaformity  I don't know if I drifted off, but did Jimmy ever address why he became such a people pleaser? He emphasized that a lot during the interview.
comments.author: @CC-mr5xq

comments.text: @CC-mr5xq  He didn't know why, it just makes him happy.  I have a Master's Degree in Psychology.  Personality traits are often inborn.  People like to make up stories about why they became a certain way, but that's just stories.  I really wish people would stop trying to make other people justify how they are, or think every way that we are is because of some trauma or some other factor.  Some people are just interested in making other people happy, other people are interested in figuring out science, other people only want to create art regardless of whether anyone else appreciates it, etc.  People are just different from each other.  What makes us happy is what makes us happy, it doesn't have to have a reason.  If you're a people pleaser to such a degree that it's harmful to you, go ahead and do whatever you need to change your behavior and take care of yourself first.  Destructive codependence doesn't help anyone.  But Jimmy enjoys making people happy.  He doesn't seem to have any signs of burnout or self-sacrifice;  on the contrary, he's loving his life.
comments.author: @shaynaformity

comments.text: @shaynaformity  I guess I'm used to watching James Lipton's Inside the Actor's Studio, who digs a bit deeper to find out actor's motivations. It also seemed to me that Jimmy looked kind of sad and dead in the eyes in this interview. Then again I was high while I was watching, so I might watch it again sober.

comments.text: I just wanted to touch on manifestation real quick since you mentioned you’re not a big believer in it. Manifestation may not be real in the sense that we can make impossible things happen just by thinking it (like winning a million dollars or curing cancer) but the more we focus on our intentions, the more our brain subconsciously looks for opportunities and experiences that draw us closer to our goals. It may look like Jimmy magically manifested his goals when we look at his life in a linear way, but most likely what happened was that he focused on his goals so intently that he subconsciously made choices and seized opportunities that helped him realize his goals

Joan Rivers had a podcast of some time after Carson died.  The lawyer was a guest on her podcast. I hope Carson was LOOKING UP and saw and heard what was said. He even apologized to her for not being able to get in touch with her. Carson had a meeting with every person that worked for him personally and members of the crew that worked in the studio for NBC, He warned everyone that if he hears of anyone speaking to Joan even if passing in the store and anyone said 1 word to her, that person would be fired immediately.
